rate pyruvate as a low-yield C3 product in iron-sulfur hydrothermal systems.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate formation from CO2 and H2 under hydrothermal iron-sulfur catalysis is supported by vent-simulation studies showing formate, acetate, and pyruvate formation on greigite/magnetite under alkaline conditions (Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Protometabolic carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe0 and FeS mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"anoxic protometabolic network; oxaloacetate recognized as unstable and transient\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Carboxylative network chemistry extends the C3 ketoacid scaffold to the C4 alpha-ketoacid oxaloacetate in an iron-promoted protometabolic setting.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Protometabolic iron-promoted networks connecting pyruvate, glyoxylate, and Krebs-like intermediates support transient oxaloacetate accessibility, though instability is a major bottleneck (Muchowska et al., 2019; Harrison et al., 2023). This connection is included as a transient hydrothermal route required by the literature-guided aspartate network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination of oxaloacetate to aspartate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe0/Fe-bearing mineral mediation\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n 