natase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted aqueous hydrolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"aqueous surface pool; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanoacetylene undergoes hydration/hydrolysis to cyanoacetaldehyde, generating the key Strecker-compatible beta-cyano aldehyde intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanoacetaldehyde as a hydrolysis product of cyanoacetylene is explicitly identified in the Sanchez-Ferris-Orgel route and in the research summary as a key branching intermediate toward asparagine/aspartate (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1966). Mineral assignment is connective but the core transformation is literature-based.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic conversion of cyanoacetylene to maleonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"308K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox system in phosphate buffer\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"35\u00b0C, UV irradiation, alkaline phosphate buffer, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Within the cyanosulfidic network, cyanoacetylene reacts in the presence of excess HCN and NH3 under UV-driven redox cycling to form dinitrile intermediates including maleonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015) explicitly identified maleonitrile as an intermediate on the route from cyanoacetylene toward alpha-aminonitrile compound 49, precursor to asparagine/aspartate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Formation of alpha-aminonitrile precursor from cyanoacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface-assisted Strecker-type chemistry\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline aqueous setting; selective partial hydrolysis remains challenging\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanoacetaldehyde undergoes Strecker-type addition of ammonia and HCN to generate the four-carbon alpha-aminonitrile precursor to asparagine and aspartate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research summary identifies cyanoacetaldehyde + NH3 + HCN as the Strecker route to a dinitrile/aminonitrile intermediate leading to asparagine upon partial hydrolysis and aspartate upon full hydrolysis (Miller & Van Trump, 1981; Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1966).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Formation of alpha-aminonitrile precursor from maleonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"308K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu photoredox-associated cyanosulfidic network\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"35\u00b0C, UV irradiation, phosphate buffer, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Maleonitrile is aminated within the cyanosulfidic network to produce the alpha-aminonitrile identified by Patel et al. as compound 49.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015) explicitly report alpha-aminonitrile compound 49 as the precursor to asparagine and aspartate in their cyanosulfidic system.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Partial hydrolysis of alpha-aminonitrile to asparagine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-308K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mild aqueous conditions favoring incomplete nitrile hydrolysis; kinetically fragile product\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Selective partial hydrolysis converts one nitrile functionality of the C4 aminonitrile into a side-chain amide while retaining the amino acid framework, giving asparagine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Partial hydrolysis of the alpha-aminonitrile precursor to asparagine is the key final step proposed for both the cyanoacetylene and cyanosulfidic routes, though selective stopping at the amide is a major unresolved challenge (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1966; Patel et al., 2015; Miller & Van Trump, 1981).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Full hydrolysis of alpha-aminonitrile to aspartate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-323K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"more extensive hydrolysis than rxn_009; thermodynamically favored relative to amide retention\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Further hydrolysis of the nitrile-bearing precursor proceeds past the amide stage to the dicarboxylate amino acid aspartate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature consistently identifies aspartate as the full-hydrolysis product corresponding to the same aminonitrile precursors that can also yield asparagine by partial hydrolysis (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1966; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct cyanoacetylene aqueous synthesis of asparagine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"aqueous mineral-supported surface setting\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"simple inorganic aqueous solution; reducing-atmosphere-derived cyanoacetylene source\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanoacetylene reacts in aqueous inorganic solution through cyanoacetaldehyde and aminonitrile intermediates to furnish both asparagine and aspartate directly within the same chemistry set.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel (1966) experimentally demonstrated that cyanoacetylene reacts with simple inorganic substances in aqueous solution to yield aspartic acid, asparagine, and cytosine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-discharge direct formation of asparagine from simple gases\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable local plasma; bulk ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"electrical discharge with non-hydrolytic analysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"reducing discharge chemistry; product only visible when analyzed without acid hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Electrical discharge through simple gaseous feedstocks generates complex nitrile-rich organics that include free asparagine among amino acid products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Jiang et al. (2014) detected asparagine directly, and as the highest-abundance amino acid, in spark discharge products using LC-MS/MS without acid hydrolysis; this reaction is represented as a direct surface-discharge route because the exact detailed microsequence was not resolved in the report.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Contact glow discharge conversion of alanine and formamide to asparagine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"discharge-heated aqueous system\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alanine 100 mM, formamide 200 mM, contact glow discharge electrolysis; reported 3.0% yield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Plasma-driven activation of alanine and formamide generates higher amino acids including asparagine through oxidative/reductive radical chemistry in aqueous formamide-containing solution.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Munegumi (2014) reported 3.0% asparagine yield from alanine and formamide under contact glow discharge electrolysis, simulating volcanic lightning chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS/FeS2 mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"anoxic hydrothermal setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-catalyzed reductive amination of the alpha-ketoacid pyruvate yields alanine, linking hydrothermal carbon fixation chemistry to later discharge-driven asparagine formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"FeS/FeS2-mediated reductive amination of alpha-ketoacids to amino acids is supported by hydrothermal iron-sulfur chemistry, and pyruvate-to-alanine conversion is a canonical example (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 2003; Barge et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Speculative prebiotic amidation of aspartate to asparagine via activating agents\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-353K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"dry-phase or low-water activity amidation using candidate activating agents cyanamide, DAP, COS, or urea; no direct demonstration for asparagine\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Activated condensation of aspartate side-chain carboxylate with ammonia is proposed to yield the side-chain amide of asparagine under dehydrating or condensing conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research report identifies amidation of aspartate as the principal unsolved bottleneck and names diamidophosphate, cyanamide, carbonyl sulfide, and urea as candidate prebiotic activating agents, but notes that none have been specifically demonstrated for asparagine formation; this reaction is therefore explicitly speculative and included only because it is necessary to connect the documented aspartate-rich network to the target (Osumah & Krishnamurthy, 2021; Schimpl, Lemmon & Calvin, 1965; Leman et al., 2004).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Deamidation of asparagine to aspartate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"thermodynamically favored hydrolysis; rapid at elevated temperature\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolytic cleavage of the side-chain amide converts asparagine to aspartate and ammonia, draining asparagine pools.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Asparagine hydrolysis to aspartate is exothermic and strongly favored; its instability is central to the literature and explains why asparagine is difficult to accumulate prebiotically (Kishore, Tewari & Goldberg, 2000; Bada, Miller & Zhao, 1995; Robinson & Robinson, 2001).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Kinetic trapping of asparagine into peptide products\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-353K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling and condensation-prone conditions; rapid incorporation proposed as escape from deamidation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Transient asparagine is incorporated into peptide-like products, reducing exposure of the free amino acid pool to hydrolytic destruction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research report highlights kinetic trapping and notes that asparagine-containing dipeptides polymerize faster than asparagine alone, suggesting peptide incorporation as a plausible escape route from deamidation (Munegumi & Tanikawa, 2017).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Sanchez-Orgel direct cyanoacetylene pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Direct aqueous cyanoacetylene chemistry yields asparagine in a surface setting.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanoacetylene hydrolysis then Strecker-type aminonitrile route\",\n      \"description\": \"Cyanoacetylene is hydrolyzed to cyanoacetaldehyde, which enters Strecker chemistry to an aminonitrile that partially hydrolyzes to asparagine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Patel cyanosulfidic route through maleonitrile\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN/H2S/UV cyanosulfidic chemistry forms cyanoacetylene, maleonitrile, then the alpha-aminonitrile precursor that partially hydrolyzes to asparagine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanoacetaldehyde branch from cyanoacetylene aqueous chemistry\",\n      \"description\": \"The Sanchez route is expanded explicitly through the cyanoacetaldehyde branch and selective partial hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct spark discharge pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Electrical discharge chemistry from simple feedstocks generates asparagine directly, detectable only without acid hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal protometabolism to aspartate then speculative amidation\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 fixation produces pyruvate, carboxylation gives oxaloacetate, transamination gives aspartate, and a speculative prebiotic amidation yields asparagine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Aminonitrile full hydrolysis to aspartate then amidation\",\n      \"description\": \"The cyanoacetaldehyde Strecker branch first yields aspartate by full hydrolysis, followed by speculative amidation to asparagine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic aminonitrile full hydrolysis to aspartate then amidation\",\n      \"description\": \"The Patel maleonitrile branch converges on the same alpha-aminonitrile, which fully hydrolyzes to aspartate and is then amidated speculatively.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate to alanine then glow-discharge asparagine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate is aminated to alanine, which in formamide under contact glow discharge yields asparagine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct asparagine formation followed by kinetic trapping\",\n      \"description\": \"Asparagine formed directly by discharge or cyanoacetylene chemistry is rapidly incorporated into peptide-like material to escape deamidation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_019\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_010\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Asparagine", "overall_strategy": "This network models asparagine as a transient, late-forming prebiotic amino acid assembled through a multi-environment system rather than a single continuous setting. Hydrothermal environments generate core carbon skeletons and protometabolic precursors such as pyruvate and oxaloacetate; surface cyanosulfidic, Strecker, and discharge chemistries generate cyanoacetylene, cyanoacetaldehyde, aminonitriles, and direct asparagine; biochemical/prebiotic settings provide limited amidation, hydrolysis control, and kinetic trapping into peptides. The network is literature-guided and explicitly reflects the major constraint that asparagine is easier to form than to preserve because deamidation to aspartate is thermodynamically favored.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "sulfane", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C3H3N", "iupac_name": "prop-2-ynenitrile", "common_name": "cyanoacetylene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3HN/c1-2-3-4/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C3H3NO", "iupac_name": "3-oxopropanenitrile", "common_name": "cyanoacetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H3NO/c4-2-1-3-5/h1,3H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C4H2N2", "iupac_name": "but-2-enedinitrile", "common_name": "maleonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H2N2/c5-3-1-2-4-6/h1-2H/b2-1+", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C4H7N3", "iupac_name": "2-aminobutanedinitrile", "common_name": "alpha-aminonitrile precursor to asparagine/aspartate", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C4H4O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxosuccinic acid", "common_name": "oxaloacetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h1H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C4H7NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminobutanedioic acid", "common_name": "aspartic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7NO4/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h2H,1,5H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C4H8N2O3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-4-carbamoylbutanoic acid", "common_name": "asparagine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8N2O3/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(7)6/h2H,1,5H2,(H2,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "formamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "CH4N2O", "iupac_name": "urea", "common_name": "urea", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4N2O/c2-1(3)4/h(H4,2,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "CH2N2", "iupac_name": "cyanamide", "common_name": "cyanamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2N2/c2-1-3/h(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "CH2N4O2P2", "iupac_name": "diamidophosphate", "common_name": "DAP", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "COS", "iupac_name": "carbonyl sulfide", "common_name": "COS", "inchi": "InChI=1S/COS/c2-1-3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C8H14N4O6", "iupac_name": "2,5-bis(2-amino-4-carbamoylbutanoylamino)pentanedioic acid", "common_name": "asparagine-containing dipeptide", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to pyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "373K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and magnetite", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline hydrothermal conditions; H2-rich; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-catalyzed CO2 fixation and sequential reduction/carboxylation generate pyruvate as a low-yield C3 product in iron-sulfur hydrothermal systems.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate formation from CO2 and H2 under hydrothermal iron-sulfur catalysis is supported by vent-simulation studies showing formate, acetate, and pyruvate formation on greigite/magnetite under alkaline conditions (Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Protometabolic carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe0 and FeS mineral surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "anoxic protometabolic network; oxaloacetate recognized as unstable and transient"}, "mechanism": "Carboxylative network chemistry extends the C3 ketoacid scaffold to the C4 alpha-ketoacid oxaloacetate in an iron-promoted protometabolic setting.", "reasoning": "Protometabolic iron-promoted networks connecting pyruvate, glyoxylate, and Krebs-like intermediates support transient oxaloacetate accessibility, though instability is a major bottleneck (Muchowska et al., 2019; Harrison et al., 2023). This connection is included as a transient hydrothermal route required by the literature-guided aspartate network."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Transamination of oxaloacetate to aspartate", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343-373K", "pressure": "moderate", "catalyst": "Fe0/Fe-bearing mineral mediation", "aqueous": true, "other": "protometabolic amination/transamination regime; oxaloacetate instability competes via decarboxylation"}, "mechanism": "Amination/transamination of the alpha-ketoacid oxaloacetate yields aspartate in iron-promoted protometabolic chemistry.", "reasoning": "Aspartate formation from oxaloacetate is literature-supported through prebiotic transamination and protometabolic networks, although oxaloacetate decarboxylation is a major competing process (Harrison et al., 2023; Muchowska et al., 2019; Springsteen et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface generation of cyanoacetylene from HCN feedstock", "inputs": ["mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu photoredox system associated with sulfide-rich UV-exposed settings", "aqueous": true, "other": "35\u00b0C, anoxic, phosphate-buffered, UV irradiation; cyanosulfidic conditions"}, "mechanism": "HCN enters UV-driven cyanosulfidic photochemistry, producing cyanoacetylene through oxidative cross-coupling chemistry in sulfide-rich surface pools.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) showed cyanosulfidic chemistry from HCN and H2S under UV with Cu photoredox cycling can generate cyanoacetylene. Mineral sulfides and UV-active surfaces are used here to place the reaction within the required surface mineral framework while retaining the literature conditions (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Hydrolysis of cyanoacetylene to cyanoacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted aqueous hydrolysis", "aqueous": true, "other": "aqueous surface pool; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Cyanoacetylene undergoes hydration/hydrolysis to cyanoacetaldehyde, generating the key Strecker-compatible beta-cyano aldehyde intermediate.", "reasoning": "Cyanoacetaldehyde as a hydrolysis product of cyanoacetylene is explicitly identified in the Sanchez-Ferris-Orgel route and in the research summary as a key branching intermediate toward asparagine/aspartate (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1966). Mineral assignment is connective but the core transformation is literature-based."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Cyanosulfidic conversion of cyanoacetylene to maleonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox system in phosphate buffer", "aqueous": true, "other": "35\u00b0C, UV irradiation, alkaline phosphate buffer, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Within the cyanosulfidic network, cyanoacetylene reacts in the presence of excess HCN and NH3 under UV-driven redox cycling to form dinitrile intermediates including maleonitrile.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) explicitly identified maleonitrile as an intermediate on the route from cyanoacetylene toward alpha-aminonitrile compound 49, precursor to asparagine/aspartate."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Formation of alpha-aminonitrile precursor from cyanoacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface-assisted Strecker-type chemistry", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline aqueous setting; selective partial hydrolysis remains challenging"}, "mechanism": "Cyanoacetaldehyde undergoes Strecker-type addition of ammonia and HCN to generate the four-carbon alpha-aminonitrile precursor to asparagine and aspartate.", "reasoning": "The research summary identifies cyanoacetaldehyde + NH3 + HCN as the Strecker route to a dinitrile/aminonitrile intermediate leading to asparagine upon partial hydrolysis and aspartate upon full hydrolysis (Miller & Van Trump, 1981; Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1966)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Formation of alpha-aminonitrile precursor from maleonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu photoredox-associated cyanosulfidic network", "aqueous": true, "other": "35\u00b0C, UV irradiation, phosphate buffer, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Maleonitrile is aminated within the cyanosulfidic network to produce the alpha-aminonitrile identified by Patel et al. as compound 49.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) explicitly report alpha-aminonitrile compound 49 as the precursor to asparagine and aspartate in their cyanosulfidic system."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Partial hydrolysis of alpha-aminonitrile to asparagine", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "mild aqueous conditions favoring incomplete nitrile hydrolysis; kinetically fragile product"}, "mechanism": "Selective partial hydrolysis converts one nitrile functionality of the C4 aminonitrile into a side-chain amide while retaining the amino acid framework, giving asparagine.", "reasoning": "Partial hydrolysis of the alpha-aminonitrile precursor to asparagine is the key final step proposed for both the cyanoacetylene and cyanosulfidic routes, though selective stopping at the amide is a major unresolved challenge (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1966; Patel et al., 2015; Miller & Van Trump, 1981)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Full hydrolysis of alpha-aminonitrile to aspartate", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-323K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "more extensive hydrolysis than rxn_009; thermodynamically favored relative to amide retention"}, "mechanism": "Further hydrolysis of the nitrile-bearing precursor proceeds past the amide stage to the dicarboxylate amino acid aspartate.", "reasoning": "The literature consistently identifies aspartate as the full-hydrolysis product corresponding to the same aminonitrile precursors that can also yield asparagine by partial hydrolysis (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1966; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Direct cyanoacetylene aqueous synthesis of asparagine", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "aqueous mineral-supported surface setting", "aqueous": true, "other": "simple inorganic aqueous solution; reducing-atmosphere-derived cyanoacetylene source"}, "mechanism": "Cyanoacetylene reacts in aqueous inorganic solution through cyanoacetaldehyde and aminonitrile intermediates to furnish both asparagine and aspartate directly within the same chemistry set.", "reasoning": "Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel (1966) experimentally demonstrated that cyanoacetylene reacts with simple inorganic substances in aqueous solution to yield aspartic acid, asparagine, and cytosine."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Spark-discharge direct formation of asparagine from simple gases", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "variable local plasma; bulk ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "electrical discharge with non-hydrolytic analysis", "aqueous": true, "other": "reducing discharge chemistry; product only visible when analyzed without acid hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "Electrical discharge through simple gaseous feedstocks generates complex nitrile-rich organics that include free asparagine among amino acid products.", "reasoning": "Jiang et al. (2014) detected asparagine directly, and as the highest-abundance amino acid, in spark discharge products using LC-MS/MS without acid hydrolysis; this reaction is represented as a direct surface-discharge route because the exact detailed microsequence was not resolved in the report."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Contact glow discharge conversion of alanine and formamide to asparagine", "inputs": ["mol_020", "mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "discharge-heated aqueous system", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "alanine 100 mM, formamide 200 mM, contact glow discharge electrolysis; reported 3.0% yield"}, "mechanism": "Plasma-driven activation of alanine and formamide generates higher amino acids including asparagine through oxidative/reductive radical chemistry in aqueous formamide-containing solution.", "reasoning": "Munegumi (2014) reported 3.0% asparagine yield from alanine and formamide under contact glow discharge electrolysis, simulating volcanic lightning chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_020"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343-373K", "pressure": "moderate to high", "catalyst": "FeS/FeS2 mineral surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "anoxic hydrothermal setting"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-catalyzed reductive amination of the alpha-ketoacid pyruvate yields alanine, linking hydrothermal carbon fixation chemistry to later discharge-driven asparagine formation.", "reasoning": "FeS/FeS2-mediated reductive amination of alpha-ketoacids to amino acids is supported by hydrothermal iron-sulfur chemistry, and pyruvate-to-alanine conversion is a canonical example (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 2003; Barge et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Speculative prebiotic amidation of aspartate to asparagine via activating agents", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_016", "mol_017", "mol_018", "mol_015", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-353K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": false, "other": "dry-phase or low-water activity amidation using candidate activating agents cyanamide, DAP, COS, or urea; no direct demonstration for asparagine"}, "mechanism": "Activated condensation of aspartate side-chain carboxylate with ammonia is proposed to yield the side-chain amide of asparagine under dehydrating or condensing conditions.", "reasoning": "The research report identifies amidation of aspartate as the principal unsolved bottleneck and names diamidophosphate, cyanamide, carbonyl sulfide, and urea as candidate prebiotic activating agents, but notes that none have been specifically demonstrated for asparagine formation; this reaction is therefore explicitly speculative and included only because it is necessary to connect the documented aspartate-rich network to the target (Osumah & Krishnamurthy, 2021; Schimpl, Lemmon & Calvin, 1965; Leman et al., 2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Deamidation of asparagine to aspartate", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-373K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "thermodynamically favored hydrolysis; rapid at elevated temperature"}, "mechanism": "Hydrolytic cleavage of the side-chain amide converts asparagine to aspartate and ammonia, draining asparagine pools.", "reasoning": "Asparagine hydrolysis to aspartate is exothermic and strongly favored; its instability is central to the literature and explains why asparagine is difficult to accumulate prebiotically (Kishore, Tewari & Goldberg, 2000; Bada, Miller & Zhao, 1995; Robinson & Robinson, 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Kinetic trapping of asparagine into peptide products", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-353K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": false, "other": "wet-dry cycling and condensation-prone conditions; rapid incorporation proposed as escape from deamidation"}, "mechanism": "Transient asparagine is incorporated into peptide-like products, reducing exposure of the free amino acid pool to hydrolytic destruction.", "reasoning": "The research report highlights kinetic trapping and notes that asparagine-containing dipeptides polymerize faster than asparagine alone, suggesting peptide incorporation as a plausible escape route from deamidation (Munegumi & Tanikawa, 2017)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Sanchez-Orgel direct cyanoacetylene pathway", "description": "Direct aqueous cyanoacetylene chemistry yields asparagine in a surface setting.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Cyanoacetylene hydrolysis then Strecker-type aminonitrile route", "description": "Cyanoacetylene is hydrolyzed to cyanoacetaldehyde, which enters Strecker chemistry to an aminonitrile that partially hydrolyzes to asparagine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Patel cyanosulfidic route through maleonitrile", "description": "HCN/H2S/UV cyanosulfidic chemistry forms cyanoacetylene, maleonitrile, then the alpha-aminonitrile precursor that partially hydrolyzes to asparagine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "n