ive to its instability, direct NH3 transamination is not well justified, and no prebiotic amidation of aspartate to asparagine has been experimentally demonstrated despite inclusion of multiple activating agents. Another issue is schema-level environmental categorization: some discharge/plasma reactions are labeled as Surface or Biochemical when they are better treated as atmospheric or geoelectrochemical contexts. Finally, because the source summary omits detailed per-reaction agents/conditions/citations, the network cannot fully satisfy the strict mineral-agent and literature-citation requirements even if the underlying chemistry is mostly consistent. Overall, this is a good but not approval-grade network under the >=0.9 threshold: excellent in literature awareness and network design, but held back by one major unresolved bottleneck and a few overconfident mechanistic assignments.\",\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.9,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.88\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_004": 0.9, "rxn_011": 0.92}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.9, "pathway_coherence": 0.94, "environmental_progression": 0.86, "target_achievement": 0.95, "overall_confidence": 0.91, "feedback": "Strong literature alignment with the classic Sanchez-Ferris-Orgel cyanoacetylene route. Direct aqueous conversion of cyanoacetylene-derived chemistry to asparagine is one of the best-supported prebiotic entries to the target. Main caveat is dependence on cyanoacetylene availability under realistically weakly reducing atmospheres.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": [], "suggestions": ["Explicitly specify the mineral/agent basis for cyanoacetylene generation and aqueous reaction conditions.", "Note atmospheric dependence and likely need for localized volcanic/reducing environments."]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_004": 0.9, "rxn_005": 0.88, "rxn_007": 0.86, "rxn_009": 0.72}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.82, "pathway_coherence"