fixation on iron-rich minerals generates C2 and C3 carboxylates from reduced carbon pools.", "reasoning": "Preiner et al. (2020) reported hydrothermal formation of acetate and pyruvate from CO2/H2 on Fe-bearing minerals; this step provides literature-supported hydrothermal precursor supply rather than direct asparagine formation."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "FeS/FeS2-mediated reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343-373K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "FeS/FeS2 mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic hydrothermal setting with NH3"}, "mechanism": "Surface-assisted reductive amination of alpha-keto acid to alpha-amino acid.", "reasoning": "Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) demonstrated FeS-based reductive amination of alpha-keto acids to amino acids; Barge et al. (2019) further supported mineral-mediated pyruvate-to-alanine conversion, though oxaloacetate decarboxylation remained problematic."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Photoredox cyanosulfidic generation of cyanoacetylene from HCN and acetylene", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite proxy for sulfidic setting)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-driven Cu photoredox in sulfidic phosphate buffer on mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic, phosphate-buffered, UV irradiated, H2S present"}, "mechanism": "Cyanosulfidic oxidative cross-coupling under UV photoredox produces cyanoacetylene from cyanide feedstock and acetylene.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) established cyanosulfidic protometabolism using HCN, H2S, UV, and Cu photoredox at about 35 degrees C; the network retains required surface mineral agents while following the reported environmental regime."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Hydrolysis of cyanoacetylene to cyanoacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted aqueous hydrolysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic aqueous pool"}, "mechanism": "Partial hydration/hydrolysis of the activated nitrile-alkyne system yields beta-functionalized aldehyde precursor.", "reasoning": "Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel (1966) proposed cyanoacetaldehyde formation from cyanoacetylene hydrolysis in aqueous prebiotic chemistry leading toward asparagine, aspartate, and cytosine."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Cyanoacetaldehyde Strecker-type conversion to four-carbon aminonitrile precursor", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_006", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-concentrating aqueous Strecker setting", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic, neutral-to-alkaline aqueous pool"}, "mechanism": "Addition of ammonia and cyanide to cyanoacetaldehyde forms a C4 alpha-aminonitrile/dinitrile precursor.", "reasoning": "Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel (1966) and Miller & Van Trump (1981) support Strecker-type access from cyanoacetaldehyde to asparagine/aspartate precursors; selective hydrolysis remains the key branchpoint."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Cyanosulfidic conversion of cyanoacetylene to maleonitrile and alpha-aminonitrile precursor", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_006", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite proxy)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV/Cu photoredox cyanosulfidic system in phosphate buffer", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic, alkaline, excess HCN and NH3"}, "mechanism": "Cyanoacetylene is funneled through maleonitrile and related nitrile intermediates to the identified alpha-aminonitrile precursor of asparagine/aspartate.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) explicitly identified maleonitrile and alpha-aminonitrile compound 49 as precursors to asparagine and aspartate under cyanosulfidic photoredox conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Partial hydrolysis of alpha-aminonitrile to asparagine", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted partial nitrile hydrolysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic aqueous pool; stopping at amide is kinetically challenging"}, "mechanism": "Selective partial hydrolysis of nitrile functionality yields side-chain amide rather than full carboxylate.", "reasoning": "Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel (1966) and Patel et al. (2015) both place selective partial hydrolysis of a nitrile precursor at the branch to asparagine; the literature emphasizes this selectivity as a major unresolved control issue."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Full hydrolysis of alpha-aminonitrile to aspartate", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "aqueous hydrolysis on mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic; greater extent of hydrolysis than rxn_008"}, "mechanism": "Further nitrile hydrolysis drives amide/carboxylate formation to aspartate.", "reasoning": "Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel (1966) and Patel et al. (2015) indicate the same aminonitrile precursor can yield aspartate upon more complete hydrolysis; this is the thermodynamically favored branch."}, {"id": "rxn_010", 