ite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"anoxic vent reactor; pyruvate reported as minor product of CO2 fixation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise mineral-catalyzed reduction and C-C bond forming fixation from CO2/H2 furnishes small ketoacids including pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate is a documented product of hydrothermal CO2 fixation on Fe-bearing minerals and is a central hub connecting hydrothermal carbon fixation to protometabolic amino-acid precursor chemistry (Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface discharge generation of HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide mineral photoredox surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"volcanic plume or atmospheric discharge microenvironment; strongly reducing local chemistry; UV/electrical energy source\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Energetic discharge/photochemical processing of simple C/N feedstocks generates cyanide that is deposited into surface pools.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN is the foundational feedstock of the asparagine network in Miller-type and cyanosulfidic chemistry. The report identifies atmospheric/discharge formation of HCN as the universal entry point to both direct and indirect routes, especially in reducing volcanic microenvironments (Miller, 1953; Patel et al., 2015; Bada, 2013). Mineral agents here represent concentration and photoredox surfaces in surface settings, not the primary energetic driver.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic formation of cyanoacetylene from HCN and acetylene\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"308K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling in phosphate buffer; mineral surfaces aid concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"anoxic, UV irradiation, phosphate-buffered surface pool; exact literature route uses HCN + acetylene + H2S under UV\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photoredox oxidative cross-coupling in cyanosulfidic chemistry converts HCN and acetylene into cyanoacetylene under anoxic UV-irradiated conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. explicitly identify cyanoacetylene generation from HCN and acetylene in a Cu photoredox H2S/UV system at about 35\u00b0C, making this one of the key direct entries to the asparagine network (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of cyanoacetylene to cyanoacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted hydration in aqueous pool\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mild aqueous hydrolysis after cyanoacetylene delivery to surface pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydration/hydrolysis of the alkyne nitrile gives the beta-cyano aldehyde cyanoacetaldehyde, the Strecker aldehyde for C4 amino-acid synthesis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Sanchez-Ferris-Orgel route and later analyses identify cyanoacetaldehyde as the key hydrolysis product of cyanoacetylene and the branch point into Strecker-type chemistry leading to asparagine and aspartate (Sanchez et al., 1966; Shapiro, 1999).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic conversion of cyanoacetylene to maleonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"308K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox system with mineral concentration surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline pH, excess HCN and NH3, UV, anoxic, phosphate buffer\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanoacetylene undergoes further cyanide/ammonia-mediated transformation under cyanosulfidic conditions to furnish maleonitrile as a nitrile-rich C4 intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. report maleonitrile as an intermediate in the integrated HCN/H2S photochemistry network en route to the alpha-aminonitrile precursor of asparagine/aspartate (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Formation of C4 alpha-aminonitrile precursor 49\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"308K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"alkaline cyanide/ammonia solution with mineral concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"anoxic, phosphate buffer, excess HCN and NH3; integrated Patel/Sanchez style nitrile chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanoacetaldehyde and related C4 nitriles react with ammonia and cyanide in Strecker-like fashion to yield a four-carbon alpha-aminonitrile/dinitrile precursor to asparagine and aspartate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature identifies a C4 alpha-aminonitrile compound (compound 49) as the explicit precursor to asparagine and aspartate in the Patel cyanosulfidic network; Sanchez et al. also invoke related aminonitrile intermediates from cyanoacetaldehyde chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Sanchez et al., 1966; Miller & Van Trump, 1981).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Selective partial hydrolysis of alpha-aminonitrile to asparagine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none established; mineral surfaces may moderate water activity\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mild hydrolysis in anoxic pool; selectivity must stop at amide rather than full acid hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"One nitrile in the C4 aminonitrile/dinitrile network is hydrolyzed only to the amide level, yielding asparagine rather than fully hydrolyzed aspartate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Direct asparagine formation from nitrile precursors is supported by the classic cyanoacetylene experiment and by Patel's identification of compound 49 as precursor to asparagine/aspartate, but the key issue is selective partial hydrolysis, which the literature emphasizes as difficult and incompletely solved (Sanchez et al., 1966; Patel et al., 2015; Miller & Van Trump, 1981).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Full hydrolysis of alpha-aminonitrile to aspartate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"aqueous hydrolysis on mineral-rich surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"prolonged hydration pushes the same precursor toward aspartate rather than asparagine\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Continued nitrile hydrolysis proceeds beyond the amide stage to the dicarboxylic amino acid aspartate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature repeatedly emphasizes that the branch between asparagine and aspartate depends on whether hydrolysis halts at amide or continues to carboxylic acid; full hydrolysis robustly yields aspartate (Sanchez et al., 1966; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-discharge production of asparagine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient to warm\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"electrical discharge; mineral deposition surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Miller-Urey-type discharge products collected and analyzed without acid hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Complex discharge chemistry from reduced atmospheric feedstocks generates amino-acid mixtures in which asparagine can be directly present but is only preserved analytically when acid hydrolysis is avoided.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Jiang et al. detected asparagine as the highest-abundance amino acid in spark-discharge products using LC-MS/MS without acid hydrolysis. The underlying mechanism is not resolved to a single step, so this node represents literature-supported direct production rather than a simple elementary reaction (Jiang et al., 2014; Miller, 1953).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal protometabolic access to oxaloacetate from pyruvate-derived networks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"room temperature to 343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"25 bar to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+/Fe0-promoted protometabolic network; mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"network-level step linking pyruvate-centered protometabolism to oxaloacetate; oxaloacetate is unstable and low persistence\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate-centered reductive carboxylation/oxidative network chemistry in iron-rich systems can access Krebs-like intermediates including oxaloacetate, albeit transiently.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature supports pyruvate-centered protometabolic networks that can reach aspartate precursors, but oxaloacetate is explicitly unstable and readily decarboxylates. This reaction is included as a network-level connector and should be interpreted cautiously rather than as a clean single-step conversion (Muchowska et al., 2019; Beyazay et al., 2023; Harrison et al., 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Cu2+-pyridoxamine transamination of oxaloacetate to aspartate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyridoxamine\", \"Cu2+\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu2+ with pyridoxamine as amine donor\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"reported approximately 5% yield within 1 hour; oxaloacetate instability is a bottleneck\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Metal-assisted PLP-analog transamination transfers amino functionality to oxaloacetate, forming aspartate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Harrison et al. demonstrated Cu2+-catalyzed transamination of oxaloacetate using pyridoxamine, not ammonia directly. This route is included exactly in that constrained form to avoid overstating support (Harrison et al., 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs-like conversion of oxaloacetate to aspartate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"cyanide, ammonia, CO2 through hydantoin/N-carbamoyl intermediates; mineral concentration surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"route parallels pyrimidine biosynthesis chemistry; compressed representation of a multistep hydantoin pathway\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Oxaloacetate reacts with cyanide, ammonia, and CO2 through carbamoyl/hydantoin intermediates to generate aspartate after hydrolytic rearrangement.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pulletikurti et al. showed alpha-ketoacids can yield amino acids through hydantoin chemistry; oxaloacetate specifically leads to aspartate via N-carbamoyl aspartate-like intermediates. This is a precursor route only, not direct evidence for asparagine (Pulletikurti et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS/FeS2 mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"anoxic hydrothermal conditions; alpha-ketoacid reductive amination chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-mediated reductive amination converts the alpha-keto acid pyruvate into alanine on Fe-S surfaces.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"FeS/FeS2 surfaces promote reductive amination of alpha-ketoacids to amino acids in hydrothermal settings and provide a literature-grounded route to alanine, which is required for the later glow-discharge asparagine route (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 2003; Barge et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface photochemical generation of formamide from HCN-containing feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV photochemistry on mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"surface pool photochemistry; representation is a necessary connector from cyanide feedstocks to the Munegumi discharge system\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical hydration/oxidation of cyanide-rich surface chemistry furnishes formamide as a concentrated C/N solvent-reactant pool component.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide is a major prebiotic solvent/reactant in surface chemistry and is directly used in the Munegumi asparagine-forming system. This connector is more general than a single dedicated experiment and is included only to bridge the literature-supported formamide discharge route into the broader network (Munegumi, 2014; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Contact glow discharge conversion of alanine and formamide to asparagine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"contact glow discharge electrolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alanine 100 mM, formamide 200 mM; reported asparagine yield about 3.0%; volcanic-lightning analogue\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Plasma/electrochemical activation of alanine and formamide under contact glow discharge generates amidated higher amino-acid products including asparagine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Munegumi directly reported asparagine formation at 3.0% yield from alanine and formamide under contact glow discharge electrolysis, making this one of the few explicit abiotic asparagine syntheses (Munegumi, 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Deamidation of asparagine to aspartate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"water\", null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-353K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"thermodynamically favored hydrolysis; rates increase strongly with temperature\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolysis of the side-chain amide converts asparagine into aspartate plus ammonia; in peptides succinimide-mediated pathways can also operate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature identifies deamidation as the central barrier to prebiotic asparagine accumulation, with exothermic hydrolysis and rapid loss at elevated temperatures; thus this sink reaction must be part of any realistic network (Kishore et al., 2000; Geiger & Clarke, 1987; Catak et al., 2009; Bada et al., 1995).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Speculative prebiotic amidation of aspartate to asparagine during drying\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"diamidophosphate\", \"cyanamide\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"condensing agents not specifically validated for this substrate\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"dry-phase concentration; included as an acknowledged unresolved gap rather than demonstrated chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Activation of a side-chain carboxylate under dehydrating conditions could in principle permit amidation to asparagine, but selectivity and yield are unknown.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction is explicitly speculative. The report states that no prebiotically plausible selective amidation of aspartate to asparagine has been demonstrated, although DAP, cyanamide, carbonyl sulfide, and urea have been discussed as possible activating agents in related chemistry. It is included only because the literature names amidation of aspartate as the key unresolved bottleneck (Osumah & Krishnamurthy, 2021; Schimpl et al., 1965; Leman et al., 2004).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Wet-dry peptide trapping of asparagine into Asn-containing dipeptides\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"ferrihydrite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay/mineral-assisted condensation\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycles in surface pools; kinetic trapping concept rather than single defined peptide product\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Dehydration-driven condensation on mineral surfaces incorporates transient asparagine into short peptides more rapidly than it persists as a free monomer.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature highlights kinetic trapping by peptide incorporation as a plausible way to preserve transient asparagine, and reports that asparagine-containing dipeptides polymerize more readily than asparagine alone. Mineral-assisted peptide formation in wet-dry settings supports this network exit from the free amino-acid pool (Munegumi & Tanikawa, 2017; Campbell et al., 2019; Kitadai et al., 2021).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Sanchez-Orgel cyanoacetylene direct route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface cyanide chemistry generates cyanoacetylene, which hydrolyzes to cyanoacetaldehyde and then proceeds through a C4 aminonitrile to asparagine by selective partial hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Patel cyanosulfidic route via maleonitrile\",\n      \"description\": \"The integrated HCN/H2S/UV surface system passes through cyanoacetylene and maleonitrile to the documented alpha-aminonitrile precursor, then to asparagine by partial hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanoacetaldehyde Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Cyanoacetylene is first converted to cyanoacetaldehyde, which enters Strecker-like nitrile chemistry with HCN and NH3 to reach the C4 aminonitrile precursor and then asparagine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-discharge direct production route\",\n      \"description\": \"Electrical discharge in reducing surface/atmospheric microenvironments yields asparagine directly in the product mixture, consistent with non-hydrolytic analysis of Miller-type experiments.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-glow-discharge route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate is reductively aminated to alanine, while surface cyanide chemistry supplies formamide; contact glow discharge then converts alanine and formamide to asparagine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Protometabolic oxaloacetate to aspartate to speculative amidation\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate-centered networks access transient oxaloacetate, which is transaminated to aspartate; dry-phase amidation to asparagine is included explicitly as unresolved and speculative.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs precursor route to speculative asparagine\",\n      \"description\": \"Oxaloacetate is converted to aspartate through hydantoin/carbamoyl chemistry, after which aspartate amidation is invoked only as an explicit literature gap.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic route through aspartate branch then speculative amidation\",\n      \"description\": \"The Patel aminonitrile precursor can fully hydrolyze to aspartate; this pathway reaches asparagine only if the unresolved amidation problem is solved during drying.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Sanchez route through aspartate branch then speculative amidation\",\n      \"description\": \"Cyanoacetylene-derived aminonitrile chemistry can produce aspartate by complete hydrolysis; asparagine requires the unresolved reverse amidation step.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Transient asparagine with peptide trapping\",\n      \"description\": \"Asparagine produced by a direct surface route is rapidly incorporated into short peptides during wet-dry cycling, providing a kinetic survival channel before deamidation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_019\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_006\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Asparagine", "overall_strategy": "This network treats prebiotic asparagine as a transient, difficult target reached by a small number of experimentally supported direct routes and several lower-confidence precursor-to-target scenarios explicitly marked as speculative at the final amidation step. The design follows the literature by centering on HCN/cyanoacetylene/cyanoacetaldehyde/aminonitrile chemistry in surface photochemical settings, while hydrothermal chemistry supplies reduced carbon hubs such as formate, pyruvate, and oxaloacetate/aspartate precursors. The network also includes destructive deamidation to aspartate and kinetic trapping into peptides as a biochemical survival strategy. Ten pathways are provided, but only those passing through cyanoacetylene chemistry, spark-discharge production, or contact glow discharge represent direct experimental support for asparagine formation; pathways relying on aspartate amidation are explicitly identified as speculative because no prebiotic selective amidation of aspartate to asparagine has been demonstrated.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formate/formic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C4H4N2", "iupac_name": "prop-2-ynenitrile", "common_name": "cyanoacetylene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H1N/c1-2-3-4-5/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C3H3NO", "iupac_name": "3-oxopropanenitrile", "common_name": "cyanoacetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H3NO/c4-2-1-3-5/h1,3H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C4H2N2", "iupac_name": "but-2-enedinitrile", "common_name": "maleonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H2N2/c5-3-1-2-4-6/h1-2H/b2-1-", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C4H5N3", "iupac_name": "2-aminobutane-1,4-dinitrile", "common_name": "alpha-aminonitrile precursor 49", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C4H5NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amidosuccinic acid", "common_name": "asparagine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8N2O3/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h2H,1,5H2,(H2,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C4H7NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminobutanedioic acid", "common_name": "aspartic acid/aspartate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7NO4/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h2H,1,5H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C4H4O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxobutanedioic acid", "common_name": "oxaloacetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h1H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "sulfane", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C2H2", "iupac_name": "ethyne", "common_name": "acetylene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2/c1-2/h1-2H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C4H6N2O2", "iupac_name": "2-aminosuccinamide", "common_name": "asparagine diamide-like partial hydrolysis intermediate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C8H14N4O5", "iupac_name": "2-(2-amidosuccinamido)succinic acid", "common_name": "Asn-Asp/Asn-containing dipeptide pool", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "373K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/mackinawite", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich; Lost City-type serpentinization context"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface reduction of CO2 by H2 on Fe-S phases yields reduced one-carbon products including formate.", "reasoning": "Fe(Ni)S-like hydrothermal minerals generate formate under alkaline vent conditions and provide the reducing-carbon feedstock that links hydrothermal carbon fixation to later surface chemistry (Preiner et al., 2020; Kelley et al., 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 fixation to pyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "373K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/magnetite", "aqueous": true, "other": "anoxic vent reactor; pyruvate reported as minor product of CO2 fixation"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise mineral-catalyzed reduction and C-C bond forming fixation from CO2/H2 furnishes small ketoacids including pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate is a documented product of hydrothermal CO2 fixation on Fe-bearing minerals and is a central hub connecting hydrothermal carbon fixation to protometabolic amino-acid precursor chemistry (Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Surface discharge generation of HCN", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide mineral photoredox surfaces", "aqueous": false, "other": "volcanic plume or atmospheric discharge microenvironment; strongly reducing local chemistry; UV/electrical energy source"}, "mechanism": "Energetic discharge/photochemical processing of simple C/N feedstocks generates cyanide that is deposited into surface pools.", "reasoning": "HCN is the foundational feedstock of the asparagine network in Miller-type and cyanosulfidic chemistry. The report identifies atmospheric/discharge formation of HCN as the universal entry point to both direct and indirect routes, especially in reducing volcanic microenvironments (Miller, 1953; Patel et al., 2015; Bada, 2013). Mineral agents here represent concentration and photoredox surfaces in surface settings, not the primary energetic driver."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Cyanosulfidic formation of cyanoacetylene from HCN and acetylene", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_017", "mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling in phosphate buffer; mineral surfaces aid concentration", "aqueous": true, "other": "anoxic, UV irradiation, phosphate-buffered surface pool; exact literature route uses HCN + acetylene + H2S under UV"}, "mechanism": "Photoredox oxidative cross-coupling in cyanosulfidic chemistry converts HCN and acetylene into cyanoacetylene under anoxic UV-irradiated conditions.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. explicitly identify cyanoacetylene generation from HCN and acetylene in a Cu photoredox H2S/UV system at about 35\u00b0C, making this one of the key direct entries to the asparagine network (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Hydrolysis of cyanoacetylene to cyanoacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted hydration in aqueous pool", "aqueous": true, "other": "mild aqueous hydrolysis after cyanoacetylene delivery to surface pools"}, "mechanism": "Hydration/hydrolysis of the alkyne nitrile gives the beta-cyano aldehyde cyanoacetaldehyde, the Strecker aldehyde for C4 amino-acid synthesis.", "reasoning": "The Sanchez-Ferris-Orgel route and later analyses identify cyanoacetaldehyde as the key hydrolysis product of cyanoacetylene and the branch point into Strecker-type chemistry leading to asparagine and aspartate (Sanchez et al., 1966; Shapiro, 1999)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Cyanosulfidic conversion of cyanoacetylene to maleonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox system with mineral concentration surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline pH, excess HCN and NH3, UV, anoxic, phosphate buffer"}, "mechanism": "Cyanoacetylene undergoes further cyanide/ammonia-mediated transformation under cyanosulfidic conditions to furnish maleonitrile as a nitrile-rich C4 intermediate.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. report maleonitrile as an intermediate in the integrated HCN/H2S photochemistry network en route to the alpha-aminonitrile precursor of asparagine/aspartate (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Formation of C4 alpha-aminonitrile precursor 49", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "alkaline cyanide/ammonia solution with mineral concentration", "aqueous": true, "other": "anoxic, phosphate buffer, excess HCN and NH3; integrated Patel/Sanchez style nitrile chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Cyanoacetaldehyde and related C4 nitriles react with ammonia and cyanide in Strecker-like fashion to yield a four-carbon alpha-aminonitrile/dinitrile precursor to asparagine and aspartate.", "reasoning": "The literature identifies a C4 alpha-aminonitrile compound (compound 49) as the explicit precursor to asparagine and aspartate in the Patel cyanosulfidic network; Sanchez et al. also invoke related aminonitrile intermediates from cyanoacetaldehyde chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Sanchez et al., 1966; Miller & Van Trump, 1981)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Selective partial hydrolysis of alpha-aminonitrile to asparagine", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none established; mineral surfaces may moderate water activity", "aqueous": true, "other": "mild hydrolysis in anoxic pool; selectivity must stop at amide rather than full acid hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "One nitrile in the C4 aminonitrile/dinitrile network is hydrolyzed only to the amide level, yielding asparagine rather than fully hydrolyzed aspartate.", "reasoning": "Direct asparagine formation from nitrile precursors is supported by the classic cyanoacetylene experiment and by Patel's identification of compound 49 as precursor to asparagine/aspartate, but the key issue is selective partial hydrolysis, which the literature emphasizes as difficult and incompletely solved (Sanchez et al., 1966; Patel et al., 2015; Miller & Van Trump, 1981)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Full hydrolysis of alpha-aminonitrile to aspartate", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "aqueous hydrolysis on mineral-rich surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "prolonged hydration pushes the same precursor toward aspartate rather than asparagine"}, "mechanism": "Continued nitrile hydrolysis proceeds beyond the amide stage to the dicarboxylic amino acid aspartate.", "reasoning": "The literature repeatedly emphasizes that the branch between asparagine and aspartate depends on whether hydrolysis halts at amide or continues to carboxylic acid; full hydrolysis robustly yields aspartate (Sanchez et al., 1966; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Spark-discharge production of asparagine", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient to warm", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "electrical discharge; mineral deposition surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "Miller-Urey-type discharge products collected and analyzed without acid hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "Complex discharge chemistry from reduced atmospheric feedstocks generates amino-acid mixtures in which asparagine can be directly present but is only preserved analytically when acid hydrolysis is avoided.", "reasoning": "Jiang et al. detected asparagine as the highest-abundance amino acid in spark-discharge products using LC-MS/MS without acid hydrolysis. The underlying mechanism is not resolved to a single step, so this node represents literature-supported direct production rather than a simple elementary reaction (Jiang et al., 2014; Miller, 1953)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Hydrothermal protometabolic access to oxaloacetate from pyruvate-derived networks", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature to 343K", "pressure": "25 bar to high", "catalyst": "Fe2+/Fe0-promoted protometabolic network; mineral surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "network-level step linking pyruvate-centered protometabolism to oxaloacetate; oxaloacetate is unstable and low persistence"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate-centered reductive carboxylation/oxidative network chemistry in iron-rich systems can access Krebs-like intermediates including oxaloacetate, albeit transiently.", "reasoning": "The literature supports pyruvate-centered protometabolic networks that can reach aspartate precursors, but oxaloacetate is explicitly unstable and readily decarboxylates. This reaction is included as a network-level connector and should be interpreted cautiously rather than as a clean single-step conversion (Muchowska et al., 2019; Beyazay et al., 2023; Harrison et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Cu2+-pyridoxamine transamination of oxaloacetate to aspartate", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["pyridoxamine", "Cu2+"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu2+ with pyridoxamine as amine donor", "aqueous": true, "other": "reported approximately 5% yield within 1 hour; oxaloacetate instability is a bottleneck"}, "mechanism": "Metal-assisted PLP-analog transamination transfers amino functionality to oxaloacetate, forming aspartate.", "reasoning": "Harrison et al. demonstrated Cu2+-catalyzed transamination of oxaloacetate using pyridoxamine, not ammonia directly. This route is included exactly in that constrained form to avoid overstating support (Harrison et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Bucherer-Bergs-like conversion of oxaloacetate to aspartate", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "cyanide, ammonia, CO2 through hydantoin/N-carbamoyl intermediates; mineral concentration surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "route parallels pyrimidine biosynthesis chemistry; compressed representation of a multistep hydantoin pathway"}, "mechanism": "Oxaloacetate reacts with cyanide, ammonia, and CO2 through carbamoyl/hydantoin intermediates to generate aspartate after hydrolytic rearrangement.", "reasoning": "Pulletikurti et al. showed alpha-ketoacids can yield amino acids through hydantoin chemistry; oxaloacetate specifically leads to aspartate via N-carbamoyl aspartate-like intermediates. This is a precursor route only, not direct evidence for asparagine (Pulletikurti et al., 2022)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343-373K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "FeS/FeS2 mineral surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "anoxic hydrothermal conditions; alpha-ketoacid reductive amination chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-mediated reductive amination converts the alpha-keto acid pyruvate into alanine on Fe-S surfaces.", "reasoning": "FeS/FeS2 surfaces promote reductive amination of alpha-ketoacids to amino acids in hydrothermal settings and provide a literature-grounded route to alanine, which is required for the later glow-discharge asparagine route (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 2003; Barge et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Surface photochemical generation of formamide from HCN-containing feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photochemistry on mineral surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "surface pool photochemistry; representation is a necessary connector from cyanide feedstocks to the Munegumi discharge system"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical hydration/oxidation of cyanide-rich surface chemistry furnishes formamide as a concentrated C/N solvent-reactant pool component.", "reasoning": "Formamide is a major prebiotic solvent/reactant in surface chemistry and is directly used in the Munegumi asparagine-forming system. This connector is more general than a single dedicated experiment and is included only to bridge the literature-supported formamide discharge route into the broader network (Munegumi, 2014; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Contact glow discharge conversion of alanine and formamide to asparagine", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "contact glow discharge electrolysis", "aqueous": true, "other": "alanine 100 mM, formamide 200 mM; reported asparagine yield about 3.0%; volcanic-lightning analogue"}, "mechanism": "Plasma/electrochemical activation of alanine and formamide under contact glow discharge generates amidated higher amino-acid products including asparagine.", "reasoning": "Munegumi directly reported asparagine formation at 3.0% yield from alanine and formamide under contact glow discharge electrolysis, making this one of the few explicit abiotic asparagine syntheses (Munegumi, 2014)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Deamidation of asparagine to aspartate", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["water", null], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-353K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required", "aqueous": true, "other": "thermodynamically favored hydrolysis; rates increase strongly with temperature"}, "mechanism": "Hydrolysis of the side-chain amide converts asparagine into aspartate plus ammonia; in peptides succinimide-mediated pathways can also operate.", "reasoning": "The literature identifies deamidation as the central barrier to prebiotic asparagine accumulation, with exothermic hydrolysis and rapid loss at elevated temperatures; thus this sink reaction must be part of any realistic network (Kishore et al., 2000; Geiger & Clarke, 1987; Catak et al., 2009; Bada et al., 1995)."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Speculative prebiotic amidation of aspartate to asparagine during drying", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["diamidophosphate", "cyanamide"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "condensing agents not specifically validated for this substrate", "aqueous": false, "other": "dry-phase concentration; included as an acknowledged unresolved gap rather than demonstrated chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Activation of a side-chain carboxylate under dehydrating conditions could in principle permit amidation to asparagine, but selectivity and yield are unknown.", "reasoning": "This reaction is explicitly speculative. The report states that no prebiotically plausible selective amidation of aspartate to asparagine has been demonstrated, although DAP, cyanamide, carbonyl sulfide, and urea have been discussed as possible activating agents in related chemistry. It is included only because the literature names amidation of aspartate as the key unresolved bottleneck (Osumah & Krishnamurthy, 2021; Schimpl et al., 1965; Leman et al., 2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Wet-dry peptide trapping of asparagine into Asn-containing dipeptides", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "ferrihydrite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay/mineral-assisted condensation", "aqueous": false, "other": "wet-dry cycles in surface pools; kinetic trapping concept rather than single defined peptide product"}, "mechanism": "Dehydration-driven condensation on mineral surfaces incorporates transient asparagine into short peptides more rapidly than it persists as a free monomer.", "reasoning": "The literature highlights kinetic trapping by peptide incorporation as a plausible way to preserve transient asparagine, and reports that asparagine-containing dipeptides polymerize more readily than asparagine alone. Mineral-assisted peptide formation in wet-dry settings supports this network exit from the free amino-acid pool (Munegumi & Tanikawa, 2017; Campbell et al., 2019; Kitadai et al., 2021)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Sanchez-Orgel cyanoacetylene direct route", "description": "Surface cyanide chemistry generates cyanoacetylene, which hydrolyzes to cyanoacetaldehyde and then proceeds through a C4 aminonitrile to asparagine by selective partial hydrolysis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_008"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Patel cyanosulfidic route via maleonitrile", "description": "The integrated HCN/H2S/UV surface system passes through cyanoacetylene and maleonitrile to the documented alpha-aminonitrile precursor, then to asparagine by partial hydrolysis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Cyanoacetaldehyde Strecker route", "description": "Cyanoacetylene is first converted to cyanoacetaldehyde, which enters Strecker-like nitrile chemistry with HCN and NH3 to reach the C4 aminonitrile precursor and then asparagine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_008"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Spark-discharge direct production route", "description": "Electrical discharge in reducing surface/atmospheric microenvironments yields asparagine directly in the product mixture, consistent with non-hydrolytic analysis of Miller-type experiments.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Hydrothermal-to-glow-discharge route", "description": "Hydrothermal pyruvate is reductively aminated to alanine, while surface cyanide chemistry supplies formamide; contact glow discharge then converts alanine and formamide to asparagine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_014", "rxn_003", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Protometabolic oxaloacetate to aspartate to speculative amidation", "description": "Hydrothermal pyruvate-centered networks access transient oxaloacetate, which is transaminated to aspartate; dry-phase amidation to asparagine is included explicitly as unresolved and speculative.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_013", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Bucherer-Bergs precursor route to speculative asparagine", "description": "Oxaloacetate is converted to aspartate through hydantoin/carbamoyl chemistry, after which aspartate amidation is invoked only as an explicit literature gap.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_011", "rxn_013", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_013", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Cyanosulfidic route through aspartate branch then speculative amidation", "description": "The Patel aminonitrile precursor can fully hydrolyze to aspartate; this pathway reaches asparagine only if the unresolved amidation problem is solved during drying.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Sanchez route through aspartate branch then speculative amidation", "description": "Cyanoacetylene-derived aminonitrile chemistry can produce aspartate by complete hydrolysis; asparagine requires the unresolved reverse amidation step.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Transient asparagine with peptide trapping", "description": "Asparagine produced by a direct surface route is rapidly incorporated into short peptides during wet-dry cycling, providing a kinetic survival channel before deamidation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_019"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_003", "mol_007", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_006"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_003", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_003"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_010", "rxn_013", "rxn_015"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_007", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_004"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_010", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_007"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_009"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_012", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_009", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_017"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_018", "rxn_019"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_006", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_011", "rxn_014"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 731223.1740951538, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-19T13:20:24.586844", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.9\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Asparagine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: This network treats prebiotic asparagine as a transient, difficult target reached by a small number of experimentally supported direct routes and several lower-confidence precursor-to-target scenarios explicitly marked as speculative at the final amidation step. The design follows the literature by centering on HCN/cyanoacetylene/cyanoacetaldehyde/aminonitrile chemistry in surface photochemical settings, while hydrothermal chemistry supplies reduced carbon hubs such as formate, pyruvate, and oxaloacetate/aspartate precursors. The network also includes destructive deamidation to aspartate and kinetic trapping into peptides as a biochemical survival strategy. Ten pathways are provided, but only those passing through cyanoacetylene chemistry, spark-discharge production, or contact glow discharge represent direct experimental support for asparagine formation; pathways relying on aspartate amidation are explicitly identified as speculative because no prebiotic selective amidation of aspartate to asparagine has been demonstrated.\n\nMOLECULES (19 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: HCN (HCN) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_004: NH3 (ammonia) [starting]\n  - mol_005: CH2O2 (formate/formic acid) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_006: C3H4O3 (pyruvate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_007: C4H4N2 (cyanoacetylene) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_008: C3H3NO (cyanoacetaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_009: C4H2N2 (maleonitrile) [intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C4H5N3 (alpha-aminonitrile precursor 49) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C4H5NO3 (asparagine) [target]\n  - mol_012: C4H7NO4 (aspartic acid/aspartate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C4H4O5 (oxaloacetate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_014: C3H7NO2 (alanine) [intermediate]\n  - mol_015: