feedstocks) [Surface]\n  - rxn_016: mol_014, mol_015 -> mol_011 (Contact glow discharge conversion of alanine and formamide to asparagine) [Surface]\n  - rxn_017: mol_011 -> mol_012 (Deamidation of asparagine to aspartate) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_018: mol_012, mol_004 -> mol_011 (Speculative prebiotic amidation of aspartate to asparagine during drying) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_019: mol_011, mol_012 -> mol_019 (Wet-dry peptide trapping of asparagine into Asn-containing dipeptides) [Biochemical]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Sanchez-Orgel cyanoacetylene direct route (5 steps)\n  - P2: Patel cyanosulfidic route via maleonitrile (5 steps)\n  - P3: Cyanoacetaldehyde Strecker route (5 steps)\n  - P4: Spark-discharge direct production route (2 steps)\n  - P5: Hydrothermal-to-glow-discharge route (5 steps)\n  - P6: Protometabolic oxaloacetate to aspartate to speculative amidation (4 steps)\n  - P7: Bucherer-Bergs precursor route to speculative asparagine (4 steps)\n  - P8: Cyanosulfidic route through aspartate branch then speculative amidation (6 steps)\n  - P9: Sanchez route through aspartate branch then speculative amidation (6 steps)\n  - P10: Transient asparagine with peptide trapping (6 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_003, mol_007, mol_010, mol_012, mol_006\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 5\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of asparagine: a persistent puzzle in origin-of-life chemistry\n\n**Asparagine stands as one of the most challenging proteinogenic amino acids to account for in prebiotic chemistry.** Its side-chain amide group undergoes rapid, thermodynamically favorable hydrolysis (deamidation) to aspartic acid under nearly all plausible early Earth conditions, creating a fundamental accumulation problem. While at least three independent experiments have demonstrated abiotic asparagine formation \u2014 from cyanoacetylene chemistry (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1966, *Science*), spark discharge analyzed without acid hydrolysis (Jiang et al., 2014, *Scientific Reports*), and contact glow discharge with formamide (Munegumi, 2014, *Bulletin of the Chemical Society of Japan*) \u2014 asparagine is broadly classified as a **\"late\" amino acid** that was likely absent from the earliest genetic code and incorporated only after enzymatic biosynthesis pathways evolved. This report synthesizes all known prebiotic routes, experimental evidence, environmental constraints, and open challenges surrounding asparagine's prebiotic origins.\n\n---\n\n## Eight proposed routes from simple molecules to asparagine\n\nMultiple pathways have been proposed or partially demonstrated for asparagine formation under prebiotic conditions. All ultimately derive from simple feedstock molecules (HCN, NH\u2083, H\u2082O, CH\u2084, H\u2082S, CO\u2082), but they diverge in mechanism, required conditions, and whether asparagine forms directly or via aspartate followed by amidation.\n\n**Route 1 \u2014 Cyanoacetylene chemistry.** The earliest and most direct demonstration comes from Sanchez, Ferris, and Orgel (1966, *Science* 154:784\u2013785). Cyanoacetylene (HC\u2083N), a major product of electric discharge through CH\u2084/N\u2082 mixtures, reacts with simple inorganic substances in aqueous solution to yield **aspartic acid, asparagine, and cytosine**. The proposed mechanism involves hydrolysis of cyanoacetylene to cyanoacetaldehyde (NC-CH\u2082-CHO), followed by further reaction with NH\u2083 and HCN to produce four-carbon aminonitrile intermediates whose partial hydrolysis yields the amide (asparagine) and full hydrolysis yields the acid (aspartate). This route requires a reducing CH\u2084/N\u2082 atmosphere, which may not reflect the CO\u2082/N\u2082-dominated early Earth (Shapiro, 1999, *PNAS* 96:4396\u20134401).\n\n**Route 2 \u2014 Cyanosulfidic protometabolism (Sutherland pathway).** Patel et al. (2015, *Nature Chemistry* 7:301\u2013307) demonstrated the most comprehensive systems-chemistry approach. Starting from **HCN and H\u2082S** with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling under UV irradiation, cyanoacetylene is generated via oxidative cross-coupling of HCN with acetylene. Further reaction with excess HCN and NH\u2083 at alkaline pH produces maleonitrile and **\u03b1-aminonitrile compound 49**, explicitly identified as the precursor to asparagine and aspartic acid. Partial hydrolysis of the nitrile to amide yields asparagine; full hydrolysis yields aspartate. Conditions are **35\u00b0C, anoxic, phosphate buffer, with UV**. This route uniquely produces amino acid, nucleotide, and lipid precursors from the same feedstock.\n\n**Route 3 \u2014 Strecker synthesis.** The classical Strecker mechanism (aldehyde + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-aminonitrile \u2192 amino acid) applies to asparagine via Route B: cyanoacetaldehyde + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 a dinitrile intermediate, whose selective partial hydrolysis yields asparagine. Miller and Van Trump (1981, in *Origin of Life*, Springer) characterized Strecker kinetics and equilibrium constants. The challenge is that the requisite \u03b2-functionalized aldehydes are less readily available prebiotically than formaldehyde or acetaldehyde, and **selective partial hydrolysis** (stopping at amide rather than proceeding to carboxylic acid) is difficult to control.\n\n**Route 4 \u2014 Bucherer-Bergs pathway from oxaloacetate.** Pulletikurti et al. (2022, *Nature Chemistry* 14:1142\u20131150) showed that \u03b1-ketoacids react with cyanide, ammonia, and CO\u2082 through hydantoin intermediates to form \u03b1-amino acids. Oxaloacetate specifically yields **aspartate** via N-carbamoyl aspartate, paralleling biological pyrimidine biosynthesis. This produces the precursor to asparagine but requires an additional amidation step.\n\n**Route 5 \u2014 Protometabolic networks.** Several groups have generated aspartate through protometabolic reaction networks: Cu\u00b2\u207a-catalyzed transamination of oxaloacetate with pyridoxamine achieves **~5% aspartate yield** within one hour (Harrison et al., 2023, *Life* 13:1177); Fe\u00b2\u207a-promoted Krebs cycle analogs from pyruvate and glyoxylate produce aspartate when hydroxylamine and Fe\u2070 are added (Muchowska et al., 2019, *Nature* 569:104\u2013107); and linked glyoxylate oxidative decarboxylation cycles generate aspartate in the presence of ammonia (Springsteen et al., 2018, *Nature Communications* 9:91). All require subsequent amidation to reach asparagine.\n\n**Route 6 \u2014 Miller-Urey spark discharge.** Miller's original 1953 experiment (*Science* 117:528\u2013529) did not report asparagine, but Jiang et al. (2014, *Scientific Reports* 4:6769) used LC-MS/MS **without acid hydrolysis** and found asparagine was the **highest-abundance amino acid** in their spark discharge products. This critical methodological difference explains decades of apparent absence.\n\n**Route 7 \u2014 Contact glow discharge.** Munegumi (2014, *Bulletin of the Chemical Society of Japan* 87:1208\u20131215) achieved asparagine at **3.0% yield** from alanine (100 mM) + formamide (200 mM) under contact glow discharge electrolysis, simulating volcanic lightning on the primordial hydrosphere.\n\n**Route 8 \u2014 Amidation of aspartate.** The biological route uses asparagine synthetase (ATP-dependent). Prebiotically, potential activating agents include diamidophosphate (DAP; Osumah & Krishnamurthy, 2021, *ChemBioChem* 22:3001\u20133009), cyanamide (Schimpl, Lemmon & Calvin, 1965, *Science* 147:149\u2013150), carbonyl sulfide (Leman et al., 2004, *Science* 306:283\u2013286), and urea. None have been specifically demonstrated for asparagine formation from aspartate.\n\n---\n\n## Key intermediates form a branching network toward asparagine\n\nThe pathway from simple molecules to asparagine passes through several critical intermediates that serve as branch points for multiple products.\n\n**Hydrogen cyanide (HCN)** is the foundational one-carbon building block in cyanosulfidic chemistry, generated photochemically or by spark discharge from N\u2082/CH\u2084 or N\u2082/CO\u2082/H\u2082 atmospheres. It feeds into both the Strecker pathway and the Sutherland systems chemistry network. **Cyanoacetylene (HC\u2083N)**, a three-carbon intermediate produced from CH\u2084/N\u2082 by electric discharge or from HCN + acetylene via Cu-catalyzed oxidative coupling, is the key branch point: it leads directly to asparagine/aspartate (Sanchez et al., 1966), to cytosine (nucleobase precursor), and to maleonitrile in the Sutherland pathway. **Cyanoacetaldehyde (NC-CH\u2082-CHO)**, formed by cyanoacetylene hydrolysis, enters Strecker-type chemistry to produce four-carbon aminonitriles.\n\n**Oxaloacetate** sits at the metabolic heart of aspartate synthesis \u2014 it is the biological precursor via transamination and appears in multiple protometabolic networks. However, it is **thermally unstable** and rapidly decarboxylates to pyruvate, particularly at elevated temperatures (Harrison et al., 2023). This instability represents a significant bottleneck. **Aspartate** itself is the immediate precursor to asparagine via amidation, accessible through at least five independent prebiotic routes described above. The critical distinction between asparagine and aspartate depends entirely on whether nitrile hydrolysis stops at the amide stage or proceeds to the carboxylic acid \u2014 a selectivity challenge with no clean prebiotic solution.\n\n| Intermediate | Formula | Role |\n|---|---|---|\n| HCN | HCN | Universal C/N feedstock |\n| Cyanoacetylene | HC\u2261C-C\u2261N | Key C\u2083 branch point to Asn, Asp, cytosine |\n| Cyanoacetaldehyde | NC-CH\u2082-CHO | Strecker aldehyde for C\u2084 amino acids |\n| Maleonitrile | NC-CH=CH-CN | Sutherland pathway intermediate |\n| \u03b1-Aminonitrile (compound 49) | H\u2082N-CH(CN)-CH\u2082-CN | Direct Asn/Asp precursor (hydrolysis-dependent) |\n| Oxaloacetate | \u207bOOC-CO-CH\u2082-COO\u207b | Protometabolic aspartate precursor (unstable) |\n| Aspartate | \u207bOOC-CH(NH\u2082)-CH\u2082-COO\u207b | Immediate asparagine precursor via amidation |\n\n---\n\n## Environmental settings each favor different steps in the synthesis\n\nNo single early Earth environment optimally supports the entire pathway from simple gases to stable asparagine. Different environments favor different steps, suggesting a **multi-environment scenario** may be required.\n\n**Alkaline hydrothermal vents (Lost City type)** operate at 40\u201390\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311, with dissolved H\u2082 at **1\u201315 mmol/kg** from serpentinization (Kelley et al., 2001, *Nature* 412:145\u2013148). Fe(Ni)S minerals (mackinawite, greigite) in vent walls catalyze CO\u2082 fixation to formate, acetate, and pyruvate (Preiner et al., 2020, *Nature Ecology & Evolution* 4:534\u2013542). Amend and Shock (1998, *Science* 281:1659\u20131662) calculated that synthesis of all 20 amino acids is **thermodynamically favorable** in hot, moderately reduced hydrothermal solutions. However, asparagine's deamidation proceeds rapidly at these temperatures, and Bada, Miller, and Zhao (1995, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres* 25:111\u2013118) argued that hydrothermal vents are **net destroyers** of organic molecules at temperatures above ~150\u00b0C. Alkaline vents are therefore best suited for generating aspartate precursors (pyruvate \u2192 oxaloacetate \u2192 aspartate) but hostile to asparagine accumulation.\n\n**Volcanic hot springs and surface pools** offer wet-dry cycling, UV irradiation, and mineral diversity. Damer and Deamer (2020, *Astrobiology* 20:429\u2013452) championed this setting for polymerization and protocell assembly. Campbell et al. (2019, *Nature Communications* 10:4508) demonstrated that deliquescent mineral mixtures self-regulate wet-dry cycling, producing glycine oligomers up to decamers. During the **dry phase**, water removal shifts equilibrium toward condensation (including potential amidation), but the subsequent wet phase subjects any asparagine formed to hydrolytic deamidation. Temperatures of **20\u201380\u00b0C** in surface pools give asparagine half-lives of weeks to months (at 25\u00b0C) to days (at 60\u201380\u00b0C), creating a narrow window for synthesis and incorporation before degradation. UV irradiation (200\u2013400 nm prebiotically relevant window; Ranjan & Sasselov, 2016, *Astrobiology* 16:68\u201388) drives the photochemistry in Sutherland's cyanosulfidic scheme.\n\n**Tidal flats** provide strictly periodic wet-dry cycling governed by tidal forces (Lathe, 2004, *Icarus* 168:18\u201322), evaporative concentration, mineral catalysis from sedimentary surfaces, and UV exposure. These settings could concentrate aspartate precursors and ammonia during evaporation while enabling condensation chemistry. **Volcanic plumes** create localized reducing microenvironments (CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S) even within an otherwise neutral atmosphere, supporting Miller-type chemistry and cyanoacetylene production (Bada, 2013, *Chemical Society Reviews* 42:2186\u20132196).\n\n---\n\n## Mineral catalysts enable specific steps but none complete the full pathway\n\n**Iron-sulfur minerals** are central to the alkaline hydrothermal vent hypothesis. Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), structurally analogous to [4Fe-4S] ferredoxin clusters, catalyzes CO\u2082 + H\u2082 fixation at 100\u00b0C producing formate (up to **200 mM**), acetate (~100 \u03bcM), and pyruvate (~10 \u03bcM) (Preiner et al., 2020). Pyrite (FeS\u2082) and freshly precipitated FeS uniquely catalyze reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoacids to amino acids (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 2003, *Tetrahedron Letters* 44:1695\u20131697), and (Ni,Fe)S coprecipitates convert amino acids to peptides at 100\u00b0C with CO (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1998, *Science* 281:670\u2013672). Awaruite (Ni\u2083Fe), naturally occurring in serpentinizing systems, catalyzes CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate at even **room temperature** under 25 bar (Beyazay et al., 2023, *Nature Communications* 14:570).\n\n**Iron oxyhydroxides (green rust/fougerite)** drive reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine at 70\u00b0C with maximum yield at **1:1 Fe(II):Fe(III) ratio** and alkaline pH (Barge et al., 2019, *PNAS* 116:4828\u20134833). Importantly, when oxaloacetate was tested, it decarboxylated to pyruvate rather than yielding aspartate \u2014 highlighting oxaloacetate's instability as a bottleneck for the aspartate pathway.\n\n**Clay minerals**, especially montmorillonite, serve primarily as concentrators and polymerization catalysts. Ferrihydrite strongly promotes aspartate dimerization, achieving Asp-Asp/Asp ratios up to **41%** \u2014 approximately **5\u00d710\u2077 times** higher than without mineral (Kitadai et al., 2021, *Minerals* 11:234). Layered double hydroxides (LDHs) from serpentinization concentrate aspartate and promote peptide formation during wet-dry cycles (Erastova et al., 2017, *Nature Communications* 8:2033). **ZnS (sphalerite)** enables reversible photocatalytic amination of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to glutamate under UV (Wang et al., 2012, *International Journal of Astrobiology* 12:69), with chiral mesostructured ZnS achieving enantiomeric excess >96% (reported 2024). No mineral has been demonstrated to specifically catalyze the amidation of aspartate to asparagine.\n\n---\n\n## Experimental evidence reveals a methodological blind spot\n\nA critical finding across all experimental studies is that **standard analytical protocols have systematically destroyed asparagine**, creating a decades-long blind spot in prebiotic chemistry. The standard 6M HCl acid hydrolysis used in virtually all Miller-Urey reanalyses, meteorite analyses, and hydrothermal experiments converts asparagine to aspartic acid by hydrolyzing the side-chain amide bond.\n\nThe three positive detections of prebiotic asparagine paint a different picture. Sanchez, Ferris, and Orgel's 1966 cyanoacetylene experiment produced asparagine directly. Jiang et al. (2014) used LC-MS/MS with pre-column derivatization **without acid hydrolysis** on spark discharge products and found asparagine was the **most abundant amino acid** \u2014 a striking result suggesting asparagine may be a quantitatively significant product of Miller-type chemistry when appropriately analyzed. Munegumi (2014) achieved a **3.0% yield** from alanine + formamide under contact glow discharge, the only quantified yield figure available.\n\nConversely, Johnson et al. (2008, *Science* 322:404) reanalyzed Miller's archived volcanic apparatus samples and detected 22 amino acids \u2014 asparagine absent due to acid hydrolysis. Parker et al. (2011, *PNAS* 108:5526\u20135531) found 23 amino acids in Miller's H\u2082S experiment archives \u2014 again, no asparagine for the same reason. The Murchison meteorite contains 70+ amino acids including aspartic acid, but **asparagine has never been reported** in any carbonaceous chondrite (Kvenvolden et al., 1970, *Nature* 228:923\u2013926; Cronin & Pizzarello, 1983). No hydrothermal vent simulation has produced detectable asparagine, consistent with its rapid thermal deamidation above 100\u00b0C.\n\n---\n\n## Deamidation creates a fundamental thermodynamic barrier\n\nThe central challenge for prebiotic asparagine is **thermodynamic**: asparagine hydrolysis to aspartate + NH\u2083 is exothermic (\u0394H \u2248 **\u221224.6 kJ/mol** at 298 K, pH 6.86; Kishore, Tewari & Goldberg, 2000, *Journal of Chemical Thermodynamics* 32:1601\u20131612) with an equilibrium constant **K >> 1**. The reverse reaction \u2014 amidation of aspartate \u2014 is energetically uphill under all prebiotically relevant conditions and worsens at higher temperatures.\n\nDeamidation proceeds through two pH-dependent mechanisms. At neutral to alkaline pH in peptide contexts, a **cyclic succinimide intermediate** forms via intramolecular nucleophilic attack, producing ~25% aspartate and ~75% isoaspartate (Catak et al., 2009, *Journal of Physical Chemistry A* 113:1111\u20131120; Geiger & Clarke, 1987, *Journal of Biological Chemistry* 262:785\u2013794). For free asparagine, direct side-chain hydrolysis predominates. Half-lives at pH 7.4 and 37\u00b0C range from **~1 day** (Asn-Gly sequences) to **~1000 days** depending on structural context (Robinson & Robinson, 2001, *PNAS* 98:12409\u201312413). At prebiotic temperatures of 60\u201380\u00b0C, free asparagine would persist for only **days to weeks**; above 100\u00b0C, deamidation occurs within **hours** (Bada et al., 1995). Thermal decomposition in the solid state begins at **~232\u00b0C** with release of H\u2082O and NH\u2083 to form polysuccinimide (Weiss et al., 2018, *BMC Biophysics* 11:2).\n\nThis instability means asparagine **cannot accumulate** in warm prebiotic oceans, hot springs, or hydrothermal systems. Even in favorable cool surface pools at 25\u00b0C, deamidation would slowly drain any asparagine reservoir. Wet-dry cycling is a double-edged sword: the dry phase thermodynamically favors condensation (potential amidation) but the wet phase immediately subjects any asparagine to hydrolysis. The net result over many cycles is unclear but likely unfavorable for asparagine accumulation.\n\n---\n\n## Asparagine was almost certainly a late addition to the genetic code\n\nMultiple lines of evidence converge on asparagine as a \"late\" amino acid absent from the earliest biological systems. Higgs and Pudritz (2009, *Astrobiology* 9:483\u2013490) classified the 20 amino acids by thermodynamic favorability and prebiotic abundance. The **10 \"early\" amino acids** \u2014 Gly, Ala, Asp, Glu, Val, Ser, Ile, Leu, Pro, Thr \u2014 appear in Miller experiments, meteorites, and thermodynamic predictions. Asparagine falls among the **10 \"late\" amino acids** (alongside Gln, Cys, Tyr, Met, Trp, His, Arg, Lys, Phe) with **zero detections** across all standard prebiotic experiments, meteorite analyses, and hydrothermal simulations.\n\nWong and Bronskill (1979, *Journal of Molecular Evolution* 13:115\u2013125) explicitly argued that asparagine's instability precludes its prebiotic origin. A particularly revealing clue comes from comparative genomics: several ancient thermophilic organisms (*Thermus thermophilus*, *Deinococcus radiodurans*) lack asparagine synthetase entirely and synthesize asparagine only via **tRNA-dependent transamidation** \u2014 the GatCAB enzyme amidates Asp-tRNA^Asn on the ribosome (Min et al., 2002, *PNAS* 99:2678\u20132683). This pathway, considered phylogenetically ancient, suggests asparagine may have originally been synthesized **on the tRNA** rather than as a free metabolite, tying its origin to the evolution of the translation machinery itself.\n\nAsparagine does play a unique and possibly underappreciated role in **homochirality**. D,L-asparagine crystallizes as a conglomerate (separate D and L crystals), enabling spontaneous optical resolution. Kojo (2010, *Symmetry* 2:1022\u20131032) demonstrated that racemic amino acid mixtures recrystallized with excess D,L-asparagine achieve up to **100% enantiomeric excess** through co-crystallization. This property, while not solving the prebiotic synthesis problem, suggests asparagine \u2014 if transiently produced \u2014 could have contributed to breaking chiral symmetry.\n\n---\n\n## Unresolved challenges and the path forward\n\nSeveral critical questions remain open in prebiotic asparagine research:\n\n- **The amidation problem** is the most fundamental. No prebiotically plausible mechanism has been demonstrated for selectively converting aspartate's side-chain carboxylate to an amide without enzymatic catalysis and ATP. Candidate activating agents (DAP, cyanamide, carbonyl sulfide, urea) remain untested for this specific transformation. This gap represents the single largest bottleneck.\n- **The analytical blind spot** deserves systematic re-examination. Jiang et al.'s (2014) finding that asparagine is the most abundant amino acid in spark discharge products \u2014 when analyzed without acid hydrolysis \u2014 demands replication and extension to other prebiotic experiments. Decades of meteorite and Miller-Urey analyses may have systematically underreported asparagine.\n- **Kinetic trapping and compartmentalization** represent possible solutions to the accumulation problem. If asparagine were incorporated into peptides or adsorbed onto mineral surfaces faster than it deamidates, transient asparagine populations could be functionally relevant even without long-term stability. Munegumi and Tanikawa (2017, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres* 47:355\u2013369) showed asparagine-containing dipeptides polymerize faster than asparagine alone, suggesting a kinetic escape route.\n- **The atmospheric composition question** remains unresolved. A reducing CH\u2084/N\u2082 atmosphere maximizes cyanoacetylene production (and thus asparagine via Sanchez et al.'s route), but the early atmosphere was likely only weakly reducing (CO\u2082/N\u2082; Catling & Zahnle, 2020). Localized reducing environments around volcanoes may reconcile this tension.\n- **The multi-environment hypothesis** \u2014 synthesis of aspartate precursors at hydrothermal vents, transport to surface pools, amidation during dry phases, and rapid incorporation into peptides \u2014 has never been tested as an integrated scenario.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nAsparagine occupies a paradoxical position in prebiotic chemistry: **it can be abiotically synthesized** (at least three independent demonstrations confirm this), yet it **cannot persist** under the very conditions that create it. The thermodynamic drive toward deamidation (\u0394H \u2248 \u221224.6 kJ/mol) and kinetic lability at warm temperatures create an accumulation crisis unmatched by most other proteinogenic amino acids. The revelation that asparagine may actually be the **dominant product** of Miller-type chemistry when properly analyzed (Jiang et al., 2014) challenges the assumption that prebiotic asparagine was negligible \u2014 the problem may not be synthesis but survival. The most plausible resolution is that asparagine was never a free prebiotic metabolite but instead entered biology through **tRNA-dependent biosynthesis from aspartate**, making it a product of early biochemical evolution rather than geochemical prebiotic chemistry. Future experiments should prioritize testing prebiotic amidation mechanisms (DAP, cyanamide, COS activation of aspartate), reanalyzing classic prebiotic experiments with non-hydrolytic analytical methods, and investigating whether mineral surfaces or peptide incorporation can kinetically trap asparagine against deamidation.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH ===\n\nConsider how well the network aligns with this literature in your evaluation.\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"<id>\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, ...},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"environmental_progression\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"target_achievement\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"feedback\": \"<pathway-specific feedback>\",\n            \"approved\": <true if confidence >= 0.8>,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_ids with issues\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"improvements\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"<id of best pathway>\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"<overall assessment>\",\n    \"hub_quality\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"convergence_quality\": <0.0-1.0>\n}\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n    {\n     