 plus formamide. The network correctly treats aspartate-to-asparagine amidation as speculative and highlights deamidation as a major sink.\\n\\nThe main limitations are chemical detail and overcompression in several reaction nodes. Some steps, especially cyanosulfidic cyanoacetylene formation, need explicit Cu photoredox conditions to fully match the literature. The hydrothermal route to oxaloacetate is under-supported and should more clearly acknowledge oxaloacetate instability. The aspartate amidation step remains the single largest weakness and prevents approval of pathways relying on it. A few reaction nodes summarize multistep sequences too aggressively, which is acceptable for network abstraction but lowers mechanistic confidence.\\n\\nOverall, the network is scientifically coherent and literature-aware, but it does not reach the approval threshold because too much of its target coverage depends on unresolved hydrolysis selectivity and speculative amidation. It is best viewed as a strong precursor-and-transient-target network rather than a robust accumulation network for asparagine.\",\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.91,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.89\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_003": 0.86, "rxn_004": 0.78, "rxn_005": 0.88, "rxn_007": 0.9, "rxn_008": 0.84}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.85, "pathway_coherence": 0.9, "environmental_progression": 0.88, "target_achievement": 0.86, "overall_confidence": 0.87, "feedback": "This is one of the strongest pathways and aligns well with the Sanchez-Ferris-Orgel and Patel-style chemistry described in the literature. The sequence from HCN to cyanoacetylene to cyanoacetaldehyde to a C4 aminonitrile and then partial hydrolysis to asparagine is chemically coherent and literature-supported in broad outline. Main uncertainty lies in rxn_004 as written, because the best-supported cyanosulfidic formation of cyanoacetylene requires Cu photoredox conditions and the network summ